Create a request against the /table endpoint

Source: R/table.R, R/table_custom.R, R/table_saved.R
sc_table.Rd

Send requests against the /table endpoint of the STATcube REST API. The requests can use three formats with corresponding functions

  • sc_table() uses a json file downloaded via the STATcube GUI

  • sc_table_custom() uses the ids of a database, measures and fields

  • sc_table_saved() uses a table uri of a saved table.

Those three functions all return an object of class "sc_table".

sc_table(
  json_file,
  language = c("en", "de"),
  add_totals = TRUE,
  key = sc_key()
)

sc_examples_list()

sc_example(filename)

sc_table_custom(
  db,
  measures,
  dimensions,
  language = c("en", "de"),
  add_totals = TRUE,
  key = sc_key()
)

sc_table_saved_list()

sc_table_saved(table_uri, language = c("en", "de"), key = sc_key())

Arguments

json_file

path to a json file, which was downloaded via the STATcube gui ("Open Data API Abfrage")
language

The language to be used for labeling. "en" or "de"
add_totals

Should totals be added for each measure in the json request?
key

(string) An API key. To display your key, call sc_browse_preferences().
filename

The name of an example json file.
db

The uid of a database
measures

A character vector of uids for measures. Can be either of type MEASURE or of type STAT_FUNCTION
dimensions

A character vector of dimensions for the cube. Can be either of type FIELD or type VALUESET. Those entries are referred to as fields in the parsed API response
table_uri

Identifier of a saved table as returned by sc_table_saved_list()

Value

An object of class sc_table which contains the return value of the httr::POST() request in obj$response. The object also provides member functions to parse this response object. See sc_table_class for the class documentation.

See also

Other functions for /table: sc_meta(), sc_write_json()

Examples

my_table <- sc_table(json_file = sc_example("population_timeseries.json"))

# print
my_table

#> An object of class sc_table
#> 
#> Database:      
#> Measures:      Number of persons 
#> Fields:        Quarter, Age in single years <96>, Sex <2>, Commune <2383> (Province-District) 
#> 
#> Request:       2021-08-11 10:53:31 
#> STATcubeR:     0.2.2

# get matadata for the table
my_table$meta

#> # STATcubeR metadata: 1 x 3

sc_table_custom(
  db = "str:database:detouextregsai",
  measures = c(
    "str:statfn:detouextregsai:F-DATA1:F-ANK:SUM",
    "str:measure:detouextregsai:F-DATA1:F-UEB"
  ),
  dimensions = c(
    "str:field:detouextregsai:F-DATA1:C-SDB_TIT-0",
    "str:valueset:detouextregsai:F-DATA1:C-C93-2:C-C93SUM-0"
  )
)

#> An object of class sc_table
#> 
#> Database:      
#> Measures:      Arrivals, Nights spent 
#> Fields:        Season/Tourism Month, Country of origin 
#> 
#> Request:       2021-08-11 10:53:44 
#> STATcubeR:     0.2.2

# get the ids and labels of all saved tables
(saved_tables <- sc_table_saved_list())

#>               label                                             id
#> 1        ts_tourism str:table:cfc581ca-dd88-44e7-9ec2-cca153365dd5
#> 2 krankenbewegungen str:table:c7902e8d-5165-44e9-b17e-34ae20e2d1d4
#> 3        tourism_ts str:table:eec7dd70-25c4-4e5a-a6ae-1a9cd15d3c4c
#> 4      entlassungen str:table:f63f0713-155f-4d1d-8d41-4a50f0815fc7
table_uri <- saved_tables$id[1]

# get a table based on one of these ids
my_response <- sc_table_saved(table_uri)
as.data.frame(my_response) %>% head()
